The constituent parts proper, then, of the play are the dialogue (diuerbium, or deuerbium as some write it) and the cantica. All iambic scenes are included as diuerbia. They had no musical accompaniment, and include all the quiet parts of the play, the ordinary narrative and dialogue, as distinguished from the excited and high- wrought scenes.
